         <abstract>
            <p>The purpose of this article is to investigate the nature of equilibrium in markets in which service and waiting time play an important role. I show that if consumers do not know which firms are charging which prices, all firms charge the same price. If firms reveal their prices by advertising, the market separates with consumers with a high (low) cost of time buying from firms with high (low) prices and short (long) queues. If firms are allowed to advertise, they will, but they benefit from a collusive agreement restricting advertisement provided the agreement is enforceable.</p>
         </abstract>
